Judas's Note:

Those that are noticing that there is &quot;minimal&quot; black bars on either side of the image is the way the bluray appears. It is not an encoding error. I choose to keep them in so that there isn't a &quot;resize&quot; stretching errors the involves splitting of pixels to fit the screen (this causes blur and other issues when there is a pixel shift always occuring... it's like being just a hair out of focus on the camera... not horrible but comparing side by side would be very noticeable if it's not 1:1 ratio)

I've also had people ask me why i occasionally have that &quot;slight&quot; hair size bar above or below, why not crop it 100% perfect? The reason is that breaking away from the 16 pixel block height results in a disadvantage in the encoding process. The moment you break the 16 pixel height tile/block it actually results in slight decrease in accuracy for the compression used. It's the difference in a 1920x800 that has a 50 block count (800/16=50) vs 1920x798 which is 49.875 block count. Things just &quot;fit&quot; and work out better overall.
